@Andrzej I think you are misunderstanding. These are NOT homonyms or homophones, which are words spelled differently but pronounced the same (which is also a common crossword theme). That kind of thing is often problematic because words can sound very different depending on accent, region, etc. it‚Äôs always an issue when connections uses homophones (same as homonyms) because not everyone pronounces those words the same way. 

Homographs (which I had to look up) are words that are spelled the same but have different meanings. They can be pronounced differently, but do not have to be. Heteronyms (a subset of honographs) are words that are spelled the same but have different pronunciations AND different meanings. For example (and I choose this example just for you üòâ), Polish and polish are heteronyms. At the beginning of a sentence they would both be capitalized, so you would need context to distinguish them.

All of the theme entry beginnings were the *correctly spelled* words for those numbers in the indicated language. Pronunciation is immaterial for this puzzle, you just have to recognize that DOS, FIRE, OTTO, and SEIZE are the words for 2,4,8,16 in other languages.

